{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_moser_ver01/data/sn85025371/00542867395/1945122701/0862.xml":{"full_text":"THE CLARKE COURIER\nESTABLISHED 1800\nPublisher: Stacy B. Lloyd, Jr.\nManaging Editor: G. Kenneth Levi\nEntered As Second Class Mail Matter at the Postoffice In\nBerryville, Virginia\nPublished Weekly At Berryville, Clarke County, Virginia\nSubscription Price: Paid in Advance $2.00 a Year; Six Months $1.25;\nThree Months $1.00\nClassified Advertising Rates two cents a word. Minimum charge\n25 cents. Display advertising rates upon request.\nEstablished first by Captain Wm. N. Nelson. Owned and edited by the\nlate John O. Crown and Joseph W. Crown for 35 years and by Ralph\nN. Dorsey for 11 years.\n^.rawing by John Austen from Don Juan osed by permission of Dodd. Meade and Co..\nPublishers.\nKate Greenaway drawings published by permission of Frederick Warne Sc Co., original publishers\nThursday, December 27. 1945\nENTER 1946\nBack in January, just over a year ago. General Eisenhower, in\nspeaking to his troops, termed 1945 as the Victory Y\u00a3ar. It was just\nafter the Germans had attempted to break through the Allied lines at\nBastogne that the General predicted that peace would come on the\nWestern Front in 1945. He had seen, and had expected, one big Ger\nman push before the Nazis would throw down their arms and call it\nquits. Had the Germans succeeded at the Belgian Bulge the war\nwould have been prolonged perhaps for months more. But the Gen\neral knew that the drive had failed, that the Nazis had thrown every\nthing they had in one big attempt to break through the lines of steel\nencircling them\u2014and had failed. They were neither prepared, nor\nhad the manpower and equipment for another big attempt.\nSo we have come to know 1945 as the Victory Year. It was the\nyear that peace had come again to the world after six long years of\nthe most horrible war of all times in which millions of people had\nbeen killed. It was the year that the attempts of Germany and Japan\nto force enslavement on the rest of the world resulted in failure\nbrought about by the might of the arms of the United Nations.\nNow we come to 1946\u2014this new year. What will it bring? Will\nit see the continuation of widespread strikes? Will it see a nation\nbeset by economic ills, of social maladjustment, governmental re\nforms and unemployment? Will it see one nation suspicious of an\nother that might one day sow the seeds of another war? What lies\nahead of us during these next twelve months?\nIt may be said that we are now entering the Atomic Age and it\nis no longer a question how many men a country can put in the field,\nbut how great are its industrial resources, and how effectively are they\norganized. The holder of the atomic bomb is a power indeed, but\nwe as its owners should place atomic energy to benefit all mankind.\nTo have peace, the world must be free, and men and women all over\nthe world are seeking that peace. After many years of ignorant and\ndull compliance to the whims and desires, of power-mad rulers, they\nare beginning to see the light. Their old fears no longer frighten\nthem and they are no longer willing to be pawns to be moved about\na checker board to benefit a few. The war has at least taught many\npeople these salient facts, and they are beginning to know that man\u2019s\nwelfare throughout the world is interdependent. They are resolved\nthat there is no place for imperialism within their own society than\nin the society o'f nations.\nIt has been said that as long as there is a world there will be wars.\nBut there need not be. We can take a great lesson from the Christ\nmas that has just passed. Christmas is the time of giving, in famil\nies, among friends and to needy far and wide. It is the time when\nfamily affection renews itself and reaches out to include others in\nits circle. From all over the world, sons and husbands have been\nhurrying home after long years of separation, and at this season\nstrangers are taken in, not for duty\u2019s sake but because for a day they\nhave ceased to be strangers, and we become just for one day more\nlike the family of God.\nBut we must find our way past the outer signs of Christmas, past\nthe greeting cards and the gifts, the family reunions and the tinseled\ntrees. We must find our wayr back to Christ and not turn our backs\non the needs of the world. We must practice the spirit of Christmas\nthe 365 days of each year, and there is no better time to start than\nJanuary, 1946. We must place giving above getting, and spread\nabroad the family affection. It is such a wonderful opportunity that\nfaces a-strong nation such as ours and we can do no better than start\nat once to place into practice such a fine and Christ-like doctrine.\nMrs. Sommaripa And 2\nOthers Hurt In Mishap\nMrs. Alice Sommaripa suffered\nminor injuries in an automobile ac\ncident Christmas Eve when the car\nshe ,was driving and her car which\nherj^enant Amos Tomblin was oper\nating skidded into each other on the\nroad to her house near Boyce.\nTraveling with Mrs. Sommaripa\nwas Mr. Tomblin\u2019s wife, and they\nwere returning from Winchester.\nShe suffered an injury to her leg.\nMrs. Sommaripa said that she and\nMr. Tomblin applied the brakes to\nthe cars when they saw each other\nand that the machines skidded to\ngether on the slippery snow. Bdth\ncars were damaged.\n-0\nBUY BONDS!\nFairly Good Weather\nPredicted For County\nSnowfalls, sleet and rain, which\ngave Clarke county a white Christ\nmas, have eased up and there isn\u2019t a\ncold wave in the immediate offing,\naccording to the weather bureau.\nThe report said the weather would\nbe fairly good for the next few days.\n_ V\nMEW YEAK.\nGREETINGS\nOur wish for 1946:\nthat our hopes for you of today\nwill be realized tomorrow and on\nall the succeeding tomorrows o:\nthe year that lies ahead.\n\nppineiS\nTo you and you and you\nOld Dominion Appliance Store\nBERRYVILLE VIRGINIA\nof 19467\nHAPPY\nNEW\nYEAR\nrpHE spirit of 1946 is Progress. So le; us\nJL all determine right now to do every\nthing a little bit better than last year, to\ntake advantage of every available oppor\ntunity for improvement, and in this way\nassure for ourselves a happier community\nof happier homes.\nAs for ourselves, we will leave no stone\nunturned to give' you still better values and\na still higher grade of service in the year\nto come.\nAnd so, wishing you all a very Happy New\nYear, we join with you in giving a royal\nwelcome to 1946.\nBERRYVILLE\nHarris\u2019 Pharmacy\nVIRGINIA","height":"25956","width":"18224"}}
